Lem: [exch] IF g . C |- X ->> X' THEN g |- C[X] ->> C[X']
Proof: By induction on -->> using [exch-one]

Lem: [exch-one] IF g . C |- e1 -> e2 THEN g |- C[e1] -> C[e2]
Proof: By induction on C. See notes for key case `x = y`.

    case C is x=y; C':

      Given

        g . (x = y; C') |- e1 -> e2

        {- by def of . -}

        (g + [g*(x) => g*(y)]) . C' |- e1 -> e2

        {- by IH -}

        (g + [g*(x) => g*(y)])  |- C'[e1] -> C'[e2]

        {- by [exch-x-y] -}

        g  |- x = y; C'[e1] -> x = y; C'[e2]

        i.e. g |- C[e1] -> C[e2]

    case C is |hole|:
        Trivial

    case C is ...C'...:
      Given
        g . ( ... C' ...) |- e1 -> e2

        {- by def of . -}

        g . C' |- e1 -> e2

        {- by IH -}

        g |- C'[e1] -> C'[e2]

        {- by [exch-id] using C = ... hole ... -}

        g |- ... C'[e1] ... -> ... C'[e2] ...
QED.

Lemma: [exch-id] If g . C == g and g |- e1 -> e2 then g |- C[e1] -> C[e2]
Proof: The redux

            g |- e1 -> e2 equiv g |- C'[x = y; E[x]] -> C'[x = y; E[y]]

       where  g . C' |- y

       As g . C[C'] = (g . C) . C' = g . C' we have

            g . C[C'] |- y

       Hence, the redux

            g |- C[e1] -> C[e2] equiv g |- C[C'[x = y; E[x]]] -> C[C'[x = y; E[y]]]

       is also valid.
QED.

Lemma: [exch-x-y]
    * IF UNION(g, x, y) |- e -> e' THEN g |- x = y; e -> e'
    * IF UNION(g, x, y) |- E -> E' THEN g |- x = y; E -> E'
Proof: "By definition" of . aka of the g |- e1 -> e2 relation. QED.

